Ikoyi builds its own spice-based cuisine around British micro-seasonality: vegetables slowly grown for flavour, sustainable, line-caught fish and aged native beef. tabindex="-1"><span class="review-full-text" style="display:none">For context, we are a mixed Nigerian family who came to celebrate my mother in laws birthday. On serving 3, we still couldnt stomach any of the meals as they were heavy on caviar and we were not enjoying the flavours. My mother in law is disabled so it was not really an option to leave, but we wanted to discuss maybe changing out some caviar for some of my family members as it was making some people genuinely uncomfortable.<br><br>We asked the head waiter if we could arrange something to change the menu, and explained that we felt disappointed at the tastes already. The waiter told us that it seems we dont understand the concept of the restaurant and we did not have the right expectations. He then sarcastically told us he could just bring some jollof rice out now which obviously hurt us very much as we are a Nigerian family, and we felt really humiliated at this point.<br><br>After that we obviously wanted to see if we could leave with a small discount (we understood upfront that we had made a reservation and the food was probably prepared in advance), but the waiter was so condescending and awful that we felt really embarrassed that we had tried to discuss that the food was sitting badly with us. We understand its an experience, but we should also feel safe to say that the experience is not working for us in every meal and work with flavours. We also felt that the waiter was really unreasonable and refused to give us any leeway even though he had already started and ended this awkward confrontation with us. We had even taken a waiter away from guests to first mention this as to not let other guests overhear us, and we believed we were being gentle and just open to the possibilities.<br><br>When we asked if we could leave with a discount, the head waiter told us again it was our fault that we didnt have the right expectations, and kept asking us if it was really the food that was the issue while looking at my Nigerian partner, as if we could not afford it. This was very heartbreaking for us and we felt very degraded, hurt and disappointed. This was a wonderful evening to celebrate my Nigerian mother in law which ended with a white waiter lecturing us and looking us up and down as if we were too poor to be there.<br><br>The other staff members were very kind and respectful, and the food got better as the night went on. Maybe this was a one time thing but its not pleasant and we thought other families may want to know.</span></span><span class="review-snippet">For context, we are a mixed Nigerian family who came to celebrate my mother in laws birthday. I asked for a different seat and was told the others (by the windows and corner) were all reserved, though there was no signage to that effect. I said we also made a reservation and arrived first. They said those tables were reserved for their 'regulars'. I asked if there was anything they could do as we came a long way to dine here especially. They said we 'should ask for a nice table next time'. Needless to say we left as the non- Black regulars arrived and took their positions at the window seats.<br><br>It is also worth noting this is meant to be a West African restaurant with no visible black staff in the kitchen.<br><br>A professed projection of sophistication as per the reviews of possible friends? class="Jtu6Td"><span jscontroller="MZnM8e" jsaction="rcuQ6b:npT2md"><span class="f5axBf" jsaction="g6zesc" data-ved="2ahUKEwj_ltPR06X-AhVC3KQKHYLkBHAQjSt6BAgBEFU"><span data-expandable-section="" tabindex="-1"><span class="review-full-text" style="display:none">I wanted to love this restaurant because it's fine dining meets Nigerian fusion. But I'm afraid it just wasn't good enough. They were nice enough to remove the crab from the jollof rice but it wasn't cooked well, the rice was a little hard and I just couldn't eat it. The plantain was an interesting twist and tasty, but there was soo little plantain even by Western standards, but it was a snack. The egusi was a deconstructed version, but it just wasn't to my taste, it was made with cabbage and the texture of the egusi itself was creamy, it just didn't work well in my opinion. The Monkfish really lacked flavour which was very disappointing. The iberico pork was tasty though. Unless the menu is changed dramatically I wouldn't go back. But for westerner's who have no idea about real Nigerian food it's something different. The restaurant itself is very central and clean but it was disappointing there was no visible African servers. The timing of the food was good!</span></span><span class="review-snippet">I wanted to love this restaurant because it's fine dining meets Nigerian fusion. But I'm afraid it just wasn't good enough. We have said this from day one but still the press and the public insist on using this label to describe our offering. We have tried to stay away from this label for this very reason; guests like yourself who come with that expectation are not able to fully experience the restaurant for what it is and we will never be able to live up to their expectations, simply because that is not what we offer. We are sorry for the inconvenience caused by the misrepresentation of our offering in the media and online, which we try to minimise but unfortunately are unable to fully control. We encourage guests to visit our website which clearly explains what we do and what we offer. We however do not make any apologies for the name of our restaurant as the reasons behind the name are personal to its owners and as it is not a word protected by a trade mark or copy right, we have style="vertical-align:top"><div class="PuaHbe" tabindex="0"><span class="lTi8oc z3HNkc" aria-label="Rated 3.0 out of 5," role="img"><span style="width:42px"></span></span><span class="dehysf lTi8oc">a year ago</span><span aria-label=","></span></div><div class="Jtu6Td"><span jscontroller="MZnM8e" jsaction="rcuQ6b:npT2md"><span class="f5axBf" jsaction="g6zesc" data-ved="2ahUKEwjGvpbS06X-AhWID-wKHZY2CUYQjSt6BQgBEMMB"><span data-expandable-section="" tabindex="-1"><span class="review-full-text" style="display:none">We felt a bit disappointed by our meal, particularly given the price tag(600 for the wine pairing / tasting menu for two). It was my husbands birthday, which I noted at the time of my reservation, and there was no acknowledgment of the occasion by any of the staff. Not a huge deal, but most fine dining restaurants that we have visited at this price point make a point to really remember the little things to make the meal special.<br><br>The food was very good - lots of great sauces and unique flavors with some real showstopper dishes. Again, we felt like there was a little lack of attention to detail - when we were served multiple small dishes, wed ask what order to eat them and the response was whatever way you want, which is a little irritating because I assume at this price point that theres more intentionality behind the meal. Really beautiful plates / bowls but some were odd choices - like a gorgeous bowl that was so tall that it was awkward to eat out of or a dish with a delicious sauce that was served with just a fork and nothing to soak up the sauce with.<br><br>But what we really left a bad taste in our mouth was the wine pairing. At 95 for five glasses of wine, we felt really underwhelmed. Several wines tasted flat and quite one note and did very little to complement the food. It did not feel like a thoughtful or interesting pairing. We asked to speak to the sommelier or the director of the beverage programme and was told that there wasnt one and everyone on staff knew bits and pieces about the wine. Im not sure how you can justify charging 95/person for what was served and without having anyone on staff who really knows and values this crucial portion of the meal.<br><br>Overall, a very tasty meal but the level of service and the beverage program do not match the price tag.</span></span><span class="review-snippet">We felt a bit disappointed by our meal, particularly given the price tag(600 for the wine pairing / tasting menu for two). class="lTi8oc z3HNkc" aria-label="Rated 3.0 out of 5," role="img"><span style="width:42px"></span></span><span class="dehysf lTi8oc">2 years ago</span><span aria-label=","></span></div><div class="Jtu6Td"><span jscontroller="MZnM8e" jsaction="rcuQ6b:npT2md"><span class="f5axBf" jsaction="g6zesc" data-ved="2ahUKEwjGvpbS06X-AhWID-wKHZY2CUYQjSt6BQgBEIUC"><span data-expandable-section="" tabindex="-1"><span class="review-full-text" style="display:none">Cosy and clean restaurant space, our server was a bit patronising she squatted next to our table to talk to us but not for any others.   I like the concept of Nigerian and Japanese flavours fusing but it didn't quite hit for all our dishes. The plantain was nice but an establishment such as this couldn't possibly mess up plantain, pairing it with ginger is classic and works very well together. My octopus was delicious, so tender and cooked to perfection the chard and red pepper emulsion were great accompaniments. The fried chicken - served complete with the entire foot and claw was not very flavourful and pink inside. I'm no stranger to 'chicken foot' but the claws are always removed prior to cooking, each to their own I'm not knocking a different culture or person's presentation it was just interesting. The chocolate, miso and sesame cookie had a chewy, sticky and  moist texture. I prefer a caramelised crunch around the circumference of my cookies but this cookie was the same soft, wettish texture throughout, it was unusual but I enjoyed it. The mango ice cream was sublime. The menu changes often so I would return to try a fish dish, the mackerel had run out the day I visited.</span></span><span class="review-snippet">Cosy and clean restaurant space, our server was a bit patronising she squatted next to our table to talk to us but not for any others.
